ALPHA DIVERSITY

Is insect visitor alpha diversity different between fruit crops and native plants across seasons?

Prepare incidence data

# Incidence_raw = species-by-sampling-unit
# matrix

bichos_long_filter$Sampling_unit <- paste("Gira",
    bichos_long_filter$Sampling_session, bichos_long_filter$Fruitcrop_transect,
    bichos_long_filter$Day, bichos_long_filter$Month,
    sep = "_")

bichos_sampling <- bichos_long_filter %>%
    group_by(Proj_season, Sampling_unit, Lowest_assignment) %>%
    summarise(n_Lowest = n()) %>%
    mutate(n_Lowest = as.integer(ifelse(n_Lowest >
        0, 1, 0)))
head(bichos_sampling, 3)

# format cultivos dry into a integer matrix

    data.frame

Completeness curve

# Sample completeness curve (type=2) with
# confidence intervals (if se=TRUE): see
# Figs. 1b and 2b in Hsieh et al. (2016).
# This curve plots the sample coverage with
# respect to sample size for the same range
# described in (1).

proj_season_compl_curve <- ggiNEXT(inext_visitors,
    type = 2)

proj_season_compl_curve_p <- proj_season_compl_curve +
    proj_season_color + proj_season_fill + pca_theme +
    annotate(geom = "text", x = 7, y = 0.56, label = "Fruit crops, Dry season (56%)",
        hjust = -0.2) + annotate(geom = "text",
    x = 10, y = 0.7, label = "Wild plants, Dry season (70%)",
    hjust = -0.2) + annotate(geom = "text", x = 22,
    y = 0.83, label = "Wild plants, Rainy season (83%)",
    hjust = -0.2) + annotate(geom = "text", x = 28,
    y = 0.85, label = "Fruit crops, Rainy season (85%)",
    hjust = -0.2) + theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 14)) +
    theme(legend.position = "none", axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), panel.border = element_blank(),
        plot.margin = grid::unit(c(5, 5, 5, 5),
            "mm"), axis.text.x = element_text(colour = "black",
            size = rel(1)), axis.text.y = element_text(size = rel(1),
            colour = "black"), axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1)))

Coverage-based curve

# Coverage-based R/E curve (type=3): see
# Figs. 1c and 2c in Hsieh et al. (2016).
# This curve plots the diversity estimates
# with confidence intervals (if se=TRUE) as
# a function of sample coverage up to the
# maximum coverage obtained from the maximum
# size described in (1)

proj_season_coverage_curve <- ggiNEXT(inext_visitors,
    type = 3, facet.var = "Order.q")

proj_season_coverage_curve_p <- proj_season_coverage_curve +
    proj_season_color + proj_season_fill + proj_season_shape +
    pca_theme + theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 14)) +
    theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), panel.border = element_blank(),
        plot.margin = grid::unit(c(5, 5, 5, 5),
            "mm"), axis.text.x = element_text(colour = "black",
            size = rel(1)), axis.text.y = element_text(size = rel(1),
            colour = "black"), axis.title = element_text(size = rel(1)))

# dev.off()

The coverage for incidence data is lower than that of abundance data. Fruitcrops during the dry season has the lowest coverage, 56%, with a reference sample size of 7 sampling units, is followed by the wild plant transects with an estimated coverage of 71% with a reference sample size of 11 sampling units. This means that 44% of individuals sampled in the dry season in fruitcrops belong to species missed during fieldwork. The coverage during the rainy season is similar for both fruitcrops and wild plant transects, estimates as 86% and 84% with a reference sample size of 36 and 26 sampling units respectively.

Hill numbers estimates (coverageD)

coverage_incidence <- estimateD(incidence_bichos,
    q = c(0, 1, 2), datatype = "incidence_raw",
    base = "coverage", conf = 0.95)

coverage_incidence$ID <- paste("Incidence", coverage_incidence$Assemblage,
    coverage_incidence$Order.q, sep = "_")

coverage_incidence_long <- coverage_incidence %>%
    select(-Assemblage, -Order.q, -t, -Method,
        -SC) %>%
    pivot_longer(!ID, names_to = "iNEXT_est",
        values_to = "estimate")

coverage_incidence_long <- coverage_incidence_long %>%
    separate_wider_delim(cols = ID, delim = "_",
        names = c("Data_type", "Project", "Season",
            "Hill_number"))

PLot Incidence Data (coverage)

season_names <- c(dry = "Dry", rainy = "Wet")

(richness_coverage_p <- coverage_incidence_long %>%
    filter(Hill_number == "0", Data_type == "Incidence") %>%

    ggplot(aes(x = Project, y = qD, group = 1)) +

    vjust = 0.9, hjust = 1)))

    pivot_wider(names_from = "iNEXT_est", values_from = "estimate") %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = Project, y = qD, group = 1)) +

    size = 4, fill = "grey") + facet_grid(~Season,
